## ğŸ“… WEEK 5 â€” Performance, Change Detection & Advanced Concepts

### âœ… Topics to Cover

| # | Topic | Level |
|---|-------|-------|
| 1 | Change Detection â€” Default vs OnPush | Advanced |
| 2 | Zone.js & `runOutsideAngular` | Advanced |
| 3 | `TrackBy` in `ngFor` | Intermediate |
| 4 | Pure vs Impure Pipes | Intermediate |
| 5 | Lazy Loading Images & Deferrable Views (`@defer`) | Advanced |
| 6 | Bundle Optimization (Tree Shaking, Code Splitting) | Advanced |
| 7 | Server-Side Rendering (Angular Universal / SSR in v17) | Advanced |

---

### ğŸ” Scenario-Based Questions â€” Week 5

> **Q1 (OnPush):** A parent component updates a list array by mutating it (`array.push()`), but the child component with `OnPush` doesn't re-render. Why and how do you fix it?
> - **Expected:** `OnPush` only detects changes via reference change. Use immutable patterns â€” spread operator or `[...array, newItem]` to create a new reference.

> **Q2 (@defer â€” Angular 17+):** A heavy analytics chart component is loaded on initial page load but most users never scroll down to it. How do you optimize this?
> - **Expected:** Use `@defer (on viewport)` â€” loads the component only when it enters the viewport. Show a `@placeholder` in the meantime.

> **Q3 (TrackBy):** You have an `ngFor` rendering 500 rows from an API. Every time a filter is applied and the list refreshes, the entire DOM is re-created. How do you fix this?
> - **Expected:** Implement `trackBy` function returning a unique `id` â€” Angular will reuse existing DOM nodes instead of destroying/recreating them.

> **Q4 (SSR):** Your Angular app's SEO is poor because search crawlers can't index dynamic content. How do you solve this?
> - **Expected:** Implement Angular SSR (Angular Universal / v17 native SSR), pre-render critical pages, use `TransferState` to avoid double API calls.

> **Q5 (Zone.js):** A real-time stock ticker component updates prices every 100ms via WebSocket. This is causing the entire app to run change detection 10 times/second. How do you optimize this?
> - **Expected:** Use `NgZone.runOutsideAngular()` to run the WebSocket listener outside Angular's zone. Only trigger `ChangeDetectorRef.detectChanges()` when needed.

